<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="ARN01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Arnot</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John Arnot was a Scottish 'disciple' of Godwin's who walked from Edinburgh to London to meet him after the publication of <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Political Justice</title>.  
He fell in love with Godwin's housekeeper <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="JON01">Louisa Jones</persName> before taking departing on a tour of Northern Europe where he visited Russia, Poland, Austria, and Germany.  
During the tour, Arnot maintained a correspondence with Godwin who in turn sent him money and kept him informed of
political events in England. Godwin also supplied an introdiction to <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HOL01">Holcroft</persName>, residing then in Germany.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">In 1798, prior to Arnot’s European sojourn, there are 19 mentions in  incl. a ‘Breakfast in 1798 with J G’ and an 
‘au matin’ meeting.  The morning meetings, paired with other instances of Arnot dining with the Godwin family, indicates a 
substantial level of intimacy.  Godwin also mentions reviewing Arnot’s manuscript and journal, and a 1799 
letter from his brother <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="ARN02">H R Arnot</persName> reveals that their father was known to have a literary reputation. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">His father is unknown but the <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title> suggests a candidate. Hugo Arnot, esq. (1749-1786) who was the author of <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">An essay on nothing. A discourse delivered in a society</title> (1776) and <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">A collection 
and abridgement of celebrated criminal trials in Scotland, from A.D. 1536, to 1784. With historical and critical remarks</title> (1785), among other works. 
 Hugo Arnot had 8 children but no details are known.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Arnot is the subject of an undated letter from Godwin to <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="TUT01">George Tuthill</persName> in which Godwin berates Tuthill for pouring 
  cold water on Arnot's plans to travel and publish his journal (MS Abinger c. 54, fols. 44-5). H R Arnot also expresses trepidation about the publication of his brother’s 
  manuscript, and urged Godwin to ensure it be published anonymously, if at all (MS Abinger c. 5, fols. 48-9). </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">There are references to Arnot in Godwin's and <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="CLA01">Mary Jane's</persName> correspondence with John Fairley, who was in the booktrade, 
 suggesting that Arnot had some connection with the booktrade in addition to his writing.</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="other">DNB</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 17, fol.68: 1798</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 5, fols. 89-90: 16 February 1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 5, fols. 128-9: 18 May 1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 7, fols. 16-17: 5,6 July 1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 20-2: 19 July1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 51-2: 10 October 1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 82-3: 26 November1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 102-3: 26 December 1800</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 120-1: 4 January 1801</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 7, fols. 1-2: 30 January 1801</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 7, fols. 9-10: 18 February 1801</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 7, fols. 11-12: 21 February1801</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="MS"> MS. Abinger c. 6, fols. 120-1: 4 January 1801</bibl><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="appearancesInDiary"><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1788"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1789"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1790"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1791"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1792"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1793"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1794"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1795"/><ab xmlns="http://www